{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"75b972fb-f7b2-41f3-b3a1-28ad95df795d","content":"It works. Here's the full program:\n\n```csharp\nusing System.Text.Json;\n\nvar options = new JsonSerializerOptions\n{\n    PropertyNamingPolicy = JsonNamingPolicy.PascalCase,\n    WriteIndented = true\n};\n\nvar person = new Person(\"Alice\", 30);\nConsole.WriteLine(JsonSerializer.Serialize(person, options));\n\npublic record Person(string name, int age);\n```\n\n**Output:**\n```json\n{\n  \"Name\": \"Alice\",\n  \"Age\": 30\n}\n```\n\n`JsonNamingPolicy.PascalCase` is a built-in policy available in .NET 11. It uppercases the first letter of each property name, so the record's lowercase `name`/`age` parameters become `Name`/`Age` in the JSON — no custom naming policy needed.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"515f3348-537a-47a7-80a2-fec41eb0f7bc","outputTokens":202,"requestId":"EC06:362ABC:BFB4EE:DFF055:69FE8557"},"id":"580f05a8-9566-4ef0-b76e-4a58ae8f7a9d","timestamp":"2026-05-09T00:52:44.147Z","parentId":"c588f233-1c4f-493a-a5f0-58c2247a159f"}
